If the UK had left the EU with no agreement at all in place (i.e., without any transition period), there could have been significant disruptions and uncertainties, including:

* Tariffs on goods traded between the UK and EU member states, as well as potential delays or disruptions to cross-border trade flows due to customs checks and other regulatory barriers;
* Changes in immigration policies that would affect both EU citizens living in the UK and British nationals residing elsewhere in Europe;
* The loss of access to certain EU programs and agencies (e.g., research funding, law enforcement cooperation) unless alternative arrangements were negotiated;
* Potential disruptions to financial services industries due to the loss of "passporting" rights that allow firms based in one EU country to provide services across the entire bloc without needing separate authorization from each member state's regulator.
